---
source: crates/normalize/tests/cli_snapshots.rs
expression: "snapshot_help(&[\"edit\", \"extract-function\"])"
---
Extract a block of code into a new function.

Usage: normalize edit extract-function [OPTIONS] [file]

Arguments:
  [file]  File path

Options:
      --jsonl                      Output one JSON object per line (for arrays)
      --lines <lines>              Line range to extract, e.g. 10-25 (1-based, inclusive)
      --pretty                     Human-friendly output with colors and formatting
      --compact                    Compact output without colors (overrides TTY detection)
      --json                       Output machine-readable JSON
      --name <name>                Name for the new function
      --apply                      Apply the changes (default: dry-run)
      --jq <jq>                    Filter output through jq expression
      --input-schema               Print JSON Schema of the subcommand's input parameters and exit
  -m, --message <message>          Message for shadow history
      --output-schema              Print JSON Schema of the subcommand's return type and exit
  -r, --root <root>                Root directory
      --manual                     Emit the reference manual for the command subtree rooted here and exit
      --params-json <params-json>  Provide all parameters as a JSON object instead of individual flags
  -h, --help                       Print help

Uses CFG liveness analysis to infer the correct parameters and return type.
By default this is a dry-run; pass `--apply` to write the changes.

Examples:
normalize edit extract-function src/lib.rs --lines 10-25 --name process_batch
normalize edit extract-function src/lib.rs --lines 10-25 --name process_batch --apply
